haracteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Innes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McInnis  , from Gaelic <b>Mag Aonghuis</b> ‘son of Aonghus’.","Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Innes in Urquhart (Morayshire), named from Gaelic <i>inis</i> ‘island’.","English: variant of   Ince  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Inniss","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Ince","meanings":["habitational name from Ince in Makerfield (Lancashire), Ince (Cheshire), or Ince Blundell (Lancashire). The placenames derive from Proto-Welsh <i>ïnïs</i> ‘island’.","possibly a post-medieval West Midlands variant of <b>Hints</b>, a habitational name from either of two places called Hints (Staffordshire, Shropshire). The placenames probably derive from Proto-Welsh <i>hïnt</i> ‘way, path’ + Middle English plural <i>-es</i>.","possibly a variant with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i> of <i>Inn</i>, from residence at an <i>inn</i> or <i>inns</i>, from Middle English <i>in</i> (singular) or <i>innes</i> (plural) ‘tavern, lodging(s), tenement(s)’. There seems also to have been some confusion with Scottish   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Inch","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: perhaps, at least in some cases, a variant of   Ince  .","English: variant of   Hinch  ."]},{"name":"McInnis","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aonghuis</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Aonghus</i> (see   Angus  ). See also   McInnes  , compare Irish   McGinnis  ."]},{"name":"Innis","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: variant of   Ince  ."]},{"name":"Inness","meanings":["Scottish (Durham and Northumberland): variant of   Innes  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Walter de Innes III of Innes - of that Ilk was born about 1180, in Europe as the son of John de Innes 2nd of Innes - of that Ilk and Lady John Flandrensis 2nd of Innes. He married Lady Walter de Innes, III about 1230. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1240, at the age of 62."},"et":{"about 1180–Abt 1240":"umbes 1180–umbes 1240","1180–1240":"1180–1240","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1200–1260":"1200–1260","1160–1225":"1160–1225","–Female":"Surnud","about 1180":"umbes 1180","before 1210":"enne 1210","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","1225":"1225","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","January 1225":"jaanuar 1225","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Europe":"Europe","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1180–Abt 1240":"noin 1180–noin 1240","1180–1240":"1180–1240","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","1200–1260":"1200–1260","1160–1225":"1160–1225","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1180":"noin 1180","before 1210":"ennen vuotta 1210","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Abt 1240":"noin 1240","1225":"1225","Abt 1200":"noin 1200","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","January 1225":"tammikuu 1225","about